Introduction¶

In this project we'll be analysing data associated with the medical appointments in Brazil and the focus is on question whether or not patients show up for their appointments. Also, we'll be interested in finding the factors that are important for us to know in order to predict if a patient will show up for their scheduled appointment.

About Data

This dataset has information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row.

  • ScheduledDay tells us on what day the patient set up their appointment.
  • Neighborhood indicates the location of the hospital.
  • Scholarship indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Famlia.
  • Be careful about the encoding of the last column: it says No if the patient showed up to their appointment, and Yes if they did not show up.

In the No-show appointments dataset there are a total of 110527 rows and 14 columns without any missing values in any columns. The descriptive statistics of the dataset shows that the Age column has minimum value of -1 and maximum of 115. From the Age histogram it can be observed that there are only a few patients above age 90. We'll normalize the Age column in the dataset in our further steps to remove these outliers.

From the histogram of the dataset, we got to know that the values for alcoholism, diabetes, hypertension, sms_received and scholarship are either 0 or 1 which signifies whether the patient is diabetic, alcoholic, and so on.

Mapping no_show column to numerical values to ease summation of count and plotting¶

In noshow columns 'No' means that the patient showed up for their appointments, and similarly 'Yes'_ means that the patient didn't show up for their appointments. So, we have changed this value to more appropriate numerical values 1 and 0 where 0 denotes No (showed up for the appointments) and 1 denotes Yes (didn't show up for the appointments.)¶

In [15]:
# Mapping no_show data column to numerical
df['no_show'].replace({'No':0,'Yes':1},inplace=True)
In [16]:
# Waiting duration between scheduled date and actual appointment date provided to patients
df['waiting_duration'] = df['appointment_date'] - df['scheduled_date']

Q.2 What is the ratio of categorical characteristics of the dataset and the no_show characteristic?¶

In order to answer this question we will find the ratio against each categorical characteristics. Firstly, we will begin with:

  • Gender
In [23]:
# Function to count values
def var_value_counts(var,index1,index2):
    total = df[var].value_counts().sum()
    cat1 = df[var].value_counts()[index1]
    cat2 = df[var].value_counts()[index2]
    return total,cat1,cat2
In [24]:
def plot_chart(var,head1,lab1,head2,lab2):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2)
    plt.subplots_adjust(left=0.125, bottom=0.1, right=1.9, top=0.9, wspace=1, hspace=1)
    
    no_show = df.groupby(var)['no_show'].value_counts()
    print("\n{}\n".format(no_show))
    
    df[var].value_counts().plot(kind='pie', title=head1, autopct="%.2f", labels=lab1, ax=axes[0]);
    grouped_no_show = df.groupby(var)['no_show'].value_counts()
    grouped_no_show.plot(kind='pie', title=head2, autopct="%.2f", labels=lab2, ax=axes[1]);

From the above charts, we can speculate that there's a huge number of appointments scheduled when the appointment was given on the same day. The maximum number of days is 179 days when the appointment was given. Since, the waiting duration contains rows that is more than 100 days, we will limit our analysis to only 30 days. Also, after 30 days the number of appointments has reduced significantly.

Conclusions¶

The analysis done in this project is not meant to be complete. This is an initial analysis report. Based on the above analysis, it can be speculated that,

  • The hospital location (neighbourhood) plays a vital role in determining the patients show up on scheduled appointment. Jardim Camburi shows the highest number of appointments with a percentage of 10.56% from the overall appointments in the neighbourhood. A basic Google search suggest that Jardim Camburi is the most populous of the entire state.
  • The shorter the appointment waiting time, the more the number of appointments scheduled. It can be seen that a total of 34.73% of appointments were scheduled and out of that, 33.10% people showed up for the appointment.
  • Patients have more likely to visit the hospital on Tuesday and Wednesday based on the no_show data.

Limitation & Assumption¶

  • The reason for people who didn't receive SMS reminder is not stated. A large segment of the patients had't received SMS and considering that in analysis will result in biasness.
  • Due to low in numbers, the age of patients greater than 90 were excluded in the analysis.
